display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex> itself.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Inductive hypothesis:</fr:strong> Assume the hypothesis holds for all field extensions of degree <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[[\Bbbk  : \mathbb {F}]<n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Inductive case:</fr:strong> Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{0}(x)]]></fr:tex> be an irreducible factor of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \in \Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> be a root of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{0}(x)]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}(\alpha )]]></fr:tex> is a subextension of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk  / \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>. If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\widetilde {\sigma }\colon \Bbbk \to \Bbbk ']]></fr:tex> extends <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma \colon \mathbb {F}\to \mathbb {F}']]></fr:tex>, then it maps <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ]]></fr:tex> to a root <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta ]]></fr:tex> of some irreducible factor <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g_{0}(x)]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(x)]]></fr:tex>, and induces <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma _{0}\colon \mathbb {F}(\alpha )\to \mathbb {F}(\beta )]]></fr:tex>. We know <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[[\mathbb {F}(\alpha ) : \mathbb {F}]]]></fr:tex> is equal to the degree of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(x)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>On the other hand, there are as many maps <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}(\alpha )\to \Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> as there distinct roots of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(x)]]></fr:tex>. Therefore there are at most <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[[\mathbb {F}(\alpha ) : \mathbb {F}]=\deg (g)]]></fr:tex> choices for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma _{0}(\alpha )]]></fr:tex>, with equality iff <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{0}(x)]]></fr:tex> is separable.</fr:p>
<fr:p>By the inductive hypothesis, each such <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma _{0}]]></fr:tex> has at most <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[[\Bbbk  : \mathbb {F}(\alpha )]]]></fr:tex> extensions to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\widetilde {\sigma }\colon \Bbbk \to \Bbbk ']]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> is also the splitting field of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}(\alpha )]]></fr:tex>, there are exactly <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[[\Bbbk  : \mathbb {F}(\alpha )]]]></fr:tex> extensions if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> is separable.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Then altogether there are at most
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[[\Bbbk  : \mathbb {F}(\alpha )][\mathbb {F}(\alpha ) : \mathbb {F}]=[\Bbbk  : \mathbb {F}]]]></fr:tex>
extensions for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\widetilde {\sigma }]]></fr:tex>, and exactly as that many if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> is separable.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
