title="Abstract Algebra">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> Theorem 13.4.27</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)=a_{n}x^{n}+…+a_{1}x+a_{0}\in \mathbb {F}[x]]]></fr:tex> be a polynomial, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi \colon \mathbb {F}\to \mathbb {F}']]></fr:tex> be a field isomorphism, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(x)\in \mathbb {F}'[x]]]></fr:tex> be a polynomial obtained by applying <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi ]]></fr:tex> to the coefficients of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex>. If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk  / \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-001S.xml"
addr="nt-001S"
title="Splitting Field of a Polynomial">splitting field</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk '/\mathbb {F}']]></fr:tex> is a splitting field of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(x)]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi ]]></fr:tex> extends to an isomorphism <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi '\colon \Bbbk \to \Bbbk ']]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
