display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (f)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Base case:</fr:strong> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (f)=1]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)=x-\alpha ]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \in \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(x)=x-\varphi (\alpha )]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> is the splitting field of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}']]></fr:tex> the splitting field of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(x)]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi ]]></fr:tex> is an isomorphism of the two trivially extending itself.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Inductive case:</fr:strong> Suppose the result holds for polynomials of degree strictly less than <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> (where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n=\deg (f)]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
<fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{1}\in \Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> be a root of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{1}(x)\in \mathbb {F}[x]]]></fr:tex> is an irreducible factor of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{1}(\alpha )=0]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Set <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F_{1}=\mathbb {F}(\alpha _{1})]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g_{1}(x)]]></fr:tex> be the polynomial obtained from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{1}(x)]]></fr:tex> by applying <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi ]]></fr:tex> to the coefficients. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g_{1}(x)]]></fr:tex> is irreducible over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}']]></fr:tex> since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{1}(x)]]></fr:tex> is irreducible over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta _{1}\in \Bbbk ']]></fr:tex> be a root of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g_{1}(x)]]></fr:tex> and set <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F'_{1}=\mathbb {F}'(\beta ).]]></fr:tex> <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-000S.xml"
addr="nt-000S"
title="Isomorphisms of fields extends to isomorphisms of simple field extensions">Isomorphisms of fields extends to isomorphisms of simple field extensions</fr:link> implies the isomorphism <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi \colon \mathbb {F}\to \mathbb {F}']]></fr:tex> extends to an isomorphism <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi _{1}\colon  F_{1}\to  F'_{1}]]></fr:tex>. Writing <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)=(x-\alpha )f_{0}(x)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(x)=(x-\beta )g_{0}(x)]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g_{0}\in  F'_{1}[x]]]></fr:tex> is obtained by applying <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi _{1}]]></fr:tex> to the coefficients of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{0}(x)\in  F_{1}[x]]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>By the inductive hypothesis, the field <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> is a splitting field for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{0}(x)]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}_{1}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Similarly, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ']]></fr:tex> is a splitting field for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g_{0}(x)]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F'_{1}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (f_{0})=\deg (g_{0})=n-1<n]]></fr:tex>, the inductive hypothesis ensures the existence of an isomorphism <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi '\colon \Bbbk \to \Bbbk ']]></fr:tex> extending <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi _{1}\colon  F_{1}\to  F'_{1}]]></fr:tex>, which itself extends <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi \colon \mathbb {F}\to \mathbb {F}']]></fr:tex>. The result follows immediately.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
